The vulnerability is SQL injection: building `DELETE FROM messages WHERE id IN (...)` by concatenating user input into the `IN` list lets an attacker inject SQL through one or more list elements.

### Why `IN (...)` is dangerous when built from input
If code does something like:
```sql
DELETE FROM messages WHERE id IN (${ids.join(',')})
```
then every item in `ids` becomes part of the SQL syntax, not just data.

Even if the app expects a list of numeric IDs, an attacker can supply crafted elements such as:
```text
["1", "2 OR 1=1"]
```
which can turn the query into something logically broader than intended, depending on how it is assembled.

More commonly, attackers abuse list inputs by injecting separators, parentheses, comments, or extra expressions in a single element, for example values shaped like:
```text
"1) OR 1=1 --"
"0) UNION SELECT ..."
"1); DELETE FROM messages; --"
```
If those strings are interpolated directly, the final SQL may no longer mean “delete these IDs”; it can mean “delete all rows” or execute additional attacker-controlled SQL, depending on the database/driver.

### Why list inputs are easy to overlook
Developers often validate that the outer input is “an array” but forget that **each array element is still untrusted**. A list does not make the contents safe. One malicious element is enough to break out of the intended `IN (...)` structure.

### Secure approach for numeric IDs
Use one placeholder per ID and pass the values separately as parameters.

Example in JavaScript:
```js
function buildBulkDelete(ids) {
  if (!Array.isArray(ids) || ids.length === 0) {
    throw new Error('ids must be a non-empty array');
  }

  for (const id of ids) {
    if (!Number.isInteger(id)) {
      throw new Error('all ids must be integers');
    }
  }

  const placeholders = ids.map(() => '?').join(', ');
  const sql = `DELETE FROM messages WHERE id IN (${placeholders})`;

  return { sql, params: ids };
}

const { sql, params } = buildBulkDelete([12, 15, 27]);
// sql: DELETE FROM messages WHERE id IN (?, ?, ?)
// params: [12, 15, 27]
```

