Use a per-type cached property metadata map so reflection runs once per `Type`, not once per object instance.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Reflection;

public static class Serializer
{
    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyInfo[]> PropertyCache = new();

    public static Dictionary<string, object?> Serialize(object instance)
    {
        var type = instance.GetType();
        var properties = PropertyCache.GetOrAdd(type, static t =>
            t.GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
             .Where(p => p.CanRead)
             .ToArray());

        var result = new Dictionary<string, object?>(properties.Length);
        foreach (var property in properties)
        {
            result[property.Name] = property.GetValue(instance);
        }

        return result;
    }
}
```

If you want to reduce per-property access overhead too, cache compiled getters:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Collections.Concurrent;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using System.Linq;
using System.Linq.Expressions;
using System.Reflection;

public static class Serializer
{
    private sealed record PropertyAccessor(string Name, Func<object, object?> GetValue);

    private static readonly ConcurrentDictionary<Type, PropertyAccessor[]> AccessorCache = new();

    public static Dictionary<string, object?> Serialize(object instance)
    {
        var type = instance.GetType();
        var accessors = AccessorCache.GetOrAdd(type, static t => BuildAccessors(t));

        var result = new Dictionary<string, object?>(accessors.Length);
        foreach (var accessor in accessors)
        {
            result[accessor.Name] = accessor.GetValue(instance);
        }

        return result;
    }

    private static PropertyAccessor[] BuildAccessors(Type type)
    {
        return type
            .GetProperties(BindingFlags.Instance | BindingFlags.Public)
            .Where(p => p.CanRead)
            .Select(p => new PropertyAccessor(p.Name, BuildGetter(type, p)))
            .ToArray();
    }

    private static Func<object, object?> BuildGetter(Type declaringType, PropertyInfo property)
    {
        var instanceParam = Expression.Parameter(typeof(object), "instance");
        var typedInstance = Expression.Convert(instanceParam, declaringType);
        var propertyAccess = Expression.Property(typedInstance, property);
        var boxedResult = Expression.Convert(propertyAccess, typeof(object));
        return Expression.Lambda<Func<object, object?>>(boxedResult, instanceParam).Compile();
    }
}
```

### Bottleneck
The expensive part is repeated reflection metadata discovery:
- `GetType()` is cheap.
- `GetProperties(...)` allocates and walks metadata.
- Filtering properties and repeated `PropertyInfo` discovery happen for every object.

In a tight loop, that means you keep paying the same metadata cost for identical types.

### Before
Typical pattern:

```csharp
foreach (var item in items)
{
    var props = item.GetType().GetProperties();
    foreach (var prop in props)
    {
        var value = prop.GetValue(item);
    }
}
```

For `n` objects of the same type with `p` properties:
- Metadata lookup per object: `O(p)`
- Value extraction per object: `O(p)`
- Total: **O(n · p)**, with reflection discovery cost paid `n` times

More explicitly:
- Reflection discovery: **O(n · p)**
- Serialization work: **O(n · p)**
- Combined remains **O(n · p)**, but with a much larger constant factor due to repeated reflection and allocations

### After caching
With a cache keyed by `Type`:
- First object of a type: metadata build `O(p)`
- Each object after that: reuse cached metadata, only read values `O(p)`

For `n` objects of one repeated type:
- One-time metadata discovery: **O(p)**
- Serialization across objects: **O(n · p)**
- Total: **O(p + n · p)** = **O(n · p)**

So the asymptotic bound is still **O(n · p)**, but the repeated reflection portion drops from **O(n · p)** to **O(p)**.

### Practical impact
Big-O doesn’t fully show the win here. The real improvement is:
- far fewer allocations
- fewer metadata table walks
- lower CPU overhead in hot loops
- better throughput when serializing many objects of the same type

### Rule of thumb
- Cache `PropertyInfo[]` if you want the simplest safe improvement.
- Cache compiled delegates too if `PropertyInfo.GetValue(...)` is also showing up hot in profiling.

