The bottleneck is the repeated linear scan through the ID vector for every query. For 10M lookups against 1M IDs, that turns into about 10^13 comparisons in the worst case.

### Before
```cpp
#include <vector>

bool contains(const std::vector<int>& ids, int q) {
    for (int id : ids) {
        if (id == q) return true;
    }
    return false;
}

void processQueries(const std::vector<int>& ids,
                    const std::vector<int>& queries,
                    std::vector<bool>& results) {
    results.clear();
    results.reserve(queries.size());
    for (int q : queries) {
        results.push_back(contains(ids, q));
    }
}
```

### Big-O before
- One membership check: **O(N)**
- Q lookups total: **O(Q × N)**
- With `N = 1,000,000` and `Q = 10,000,000`, this is infeasible at scale.

### Optimized approach
Build a hash set once, then do average constant-time membership checks.

```cpp
#include <vector>
#include <unordered_set>

void processQueries(const std::vector<int>& ids,
                    const std::vector<int>& queries,
                    std::vector<bool>& results) {
    std::unordered_set<int> idSet;
    idSet.reserve(ids.size());
    idSet.insert(ids.begin(), ids.end());

    results.clear();
    results.reserve(queries.size());
    for (int q : queries) {
        results.push_back(idSet.find(q) != idSet.end());
    }
}
```

### Big-O after
- Build hash set: **O(N)** average
- One membership check: **O(1)** average
- Q lookups total: **O(N + Q)** average

For 1M IDs and 10M queries, this is dramatically faster because you pay the preprocessing cost once instead of rescanning the vector 10M times.

### Notes
- `std::unordered_set` is the best fit if you only need existence checks.
- `reserve(ids.size())` helps reduce rehashing overhead.
- If worst-case guarantees matter, `std::set` gives **O(log N)** lookups, but is usually slower than `unordered_set` in practice for this workload.

If you want, I can also show a `sort + binary_search` version and compare its tradeoffs against `unordered_set`.

