Use a `DocumentFragment` or build the nodes off-DOM, then append once.

```js
const container = document.getElementById('list');
const fragment = document.createDocumentFragment();

for (let i = 0; i < 20000; i++) {
  const el = document.createElement('div');
  el.textContent = `Item ${i}`;
  fragment.appendChild(el);
}

container.appendChild(fragment);
```

If the content is simple and trusted, `innerHTML` can also be fast:

```js
const container = document.getElementById('list');
let html = '';

for (let i = 0; i < 20000; i++) {
  html += `<div>Item ${i}</div>`;
}

container.innerHTML = html;
```

## Bottleneck
Appending directly to the live DOM in each loop iteration can trigger repeated style recalculation, layout, paint, and tree mutation work. Even when browsers batch some work, touching the live DOM 20,000 times creates much more overhead than preparing the subtree once and inserting it once.

## Analysis
Let `n` be the number of elements.

### Before
```js
for (let i = 0; i < n; i++) {
  const el = document.createElement('div');
  el.textContent = `Item ${i}`;
  container.appendChild(el);
}
```

- Node creation: **O(n)**
- Live DOM insertions: **O(n)**
- Potential layout/style work: up to **O(n)** triggers, often making total practical cost much worse
- Rough practical model: **O(n + n·R)** where `R` is per-insert render/layout overhead
- In pessimistic cases, if each insertion causes work proportional to current DOM size, behavior can approach **O(n²)**

### After (`DocumentFragment`)
- Node creation: **O(n)**
- Fragment insertions: **O(n)**, but off-DOM and cheap
- Live DOM insertion: **O(1)** append of the fragment root operation, with one main render/layout pass afterward
- Total practical cost: **O(n + R)**, usually simplified to **O(n)**

## Why this helps
You still create 20,000 nodes, so you cannot do better than **O(n)** overall for construction. The optimization removes most of the repeated expensive work against the live document, reducing constant factors dramatically and avoiding possible near-quadratic behavior from repeated reflow.

