const formattedUsers = useMemo(() => {
  const cache = new Map<string, string>();

  const formatUserMemo = (user: User) => {
    const key = `${user.id}|${user.name}|${user.role}|${user.lastSeenAt}`;
    let value = cache.get(key);
    if (value === undefined) {
      value = expensiveFormatUser(user);
      cache.set(key, value);
    }
    return value;
  };

  return users.map(user => ({
    id: user.id,
    label: formatUserMemo(user),
    tooltip: formatUserMemo(user),
    searchText: formatUserMemo(user),
  }));
}, [users]);
```

## Bottleneck
The bottleneck is repeated execution of the same expensive pure function for the same logical input within one render cycle.

## Big-O
Let:
- `n` = number of items rendered
- `k` = number of repeated calls per item
- `T` = cost of the expensive transformation

Before:
- Time: **O(n · k · T)**
- Space: **O(1)** extra

After memoization:
- Time: **O(n · T + n · k)** on average, typically simplified to **O(n · T)** when cache lookup is O(1)
- Space: **O(n)** for the cache

If many items are duplicates by value, the post-memoization time is better expressed as:
- Time: **O(u · T + n · k)** where `u` is the number of unique inputs and `u <= n`

## When to use
This is correct when the function is:
- deterministic/pure for a given input
- expensive enough to justify cache overhead
- repeatedly called with identical inputs during a render

